# Requirements: __PROJECT_NAME__

> Updated on: __DATE__
>
> This document covers what / why, not how.

## 1. Summary

[Deliver a browser-first product where users can complete the core flow on key pages and clearly understand the current state and next action.]

## 2. User Stories

- `US-001` As a first-time visitor, I want to understand the main value quickly and complete the first core action so I can decide whether the product is worth using
- `US-002` As a returning user, I want to see status, results, and error guidance in the interface so I can continue the task I started

## 3. Functional Requirements

| ID | Description | Why it matters | Priority |
|---|---|---|---|
| `FR-001` | Users can complete the first core flow on a key page | Reduces first-use friction and early drop-off | H |
| `FR-002` | Users can see current state, error guidance, and next actions in the interface | Improves recoverability and reduces failure cost | H |

## 4. Non-Functional Requirements

| ID | Description | How to measure |
|---|---|---|
| `NFR-001` | Key pages should become interactive within 3 seconds under the target network condition | Measure with browser performance metrics or Web Vitals |
| `NFR-002` | UI error messages must not expose internal implementation details or sensitive information | Review displayed error content and logging strategy |

## 5. Acceptance Criteria

| ID | Requirement | Acceptance condition |
|---|---|---|
| `AC-001` | `FR-001` | A user can start the first core flow from the key page without needing extra documentation |
| `AC-002` | `FR-002` | On request or validation failure, the UI shows a clear, recoverable message and preserves needed context |

## 6. Priorities and Version Boundaries

| Requirement | Priority | Target version | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `FR-001` | H | V1 | Without a complete first flow, the value of the web product cannot be validated |
| `FR-002` | H | V1 | State and error feedback are fundamental to usability |

## 7. Out of Scope

- Native mobile applications
- Complex operations back offices or multi-role permission systems

## 8. External Dependencies and Constraints

- Browser runtime environment
- Backend APIs or a BFF
- Design system, component guidelines, or brand constraints

## 8.1 Beginner Fill-In Prompts

If you are not sure how to write this yet, answer these first:

| Question | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Which page is the most important V1 page? | Without a key page, the first complete flow cannot be focused |
| Are users mainly on mobile or desktop? | This shapes experience goals and later design rules |
| Are login, permissions, or multi-role flows required? | This changes scope and user flows |
| Is there already a brand color, typography, or component system? | This shapes visual and component expectations in design |
| Which browsers and minimum device capabilities must be supported? | This defines compatibility and performance boundaries |

## 8.2 Copyable V1 Example

For a common dashboard or tool-style web product, you can start with:

- V1 key page: post-login home page or the main list page
- V1 core flow: create one record, view its status, update one key field
- V1 required feedback: loading, success, failure, and empty state
- V2 candidates: multi-role permissions, complex reports, bulk actions, theme switching

## 9. Requirements Checklist

- Every `FR-*` can be verified on its own
- Every high-priority requirement maps to at least one `AC-*`
- This document does not contain stack, database, component, or implementation details
- A reader should understand what the project does without reading code

## 10. Open Questions

- What exactly is the first core flow on the key page?
- Are there authentication, authorization, or multi-role scenarios?
- Which browsers and minimum device capabilities must be supported?
- Is there an existing brand, font, component library, or design system constraint?

## 10.1 Common Mistakes

Wrong:

- "Use React for the homepage, TanStack Table for lists, and a specific UI kit for forms."

Better:

- "Users can complete the primary create, view, and update flow on the key page."

